AGI -&nbsp; Israel granted Hamas a week to accept the hostage agreement, otherwise it will launch the offensive promised to Rafah for a long time. The Wall Street Journal reports that it does not specify when the ultimatum was given, but mentions Egyptian officials who spoke today, which means that Hamas will have time until next Friday to accept the agreement.&nbsp; Meanwhile, CIA director William Burns arrived in Cairo for a series of meetings on the conflict in Gaza. A source of Egyptian security and three sources told Cairo airport that the Israeli media reported. Egypt, along with Qatar and the United States, is leading mediation efforts between Israel and Hamas to mediate an agreement for the ceasefire and release of hostages in Gaza.&nbsp; A delegation from the Palestinian group will also be present in Cairo. Hamas underlines his "positive spirit" towards the recently received hostage proposal. "We are determined to ensure an agreement to meet the demands of the Palestinians," says the terrorist group in a note.
&nbsp;
Ultimatum or not, a high official of the Islamist movement accused Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu to boycott any prospect of truce while continuing to talk about the prospect of a land operation against Rafah. Hamas is discussing what to do within his leadership and with allied groups, said Hossam Badran at the Afp, but he warned that Netanyahu's statements were thought to "contrasting every chance to conclude an agreement". &nbsp;
&nbsp;
"Netanyahu was the instructor in all previous rounds of dialogue and negotiations, and it is clear that it is still", he said in a telephone interview, "is not interested in reaching an agreement". The mediators of Egypt, Qatar and the United States proposed an agreement that would end the fighting for 40 days and would exchange Israeli hostages with potentially thousands of Palestinian prisoners, according to the details previously released by Britain. The outcome of the indirect negotiations was highly uncertain, with forward and backward the number of hostages that could be released and profound differences in the scope of any agreement. Badran reiterated that Hamas' goal remains a lasting ceasefire and "a complete and global withdrawal of employment forces from the Gaza Strip". This goal is in contrast to Netanyahu's declared position, which promised that the army will continue to fight Hamas, even at Rafah. But after months of alternating current negotiations, the head of the Hamas political office based in Qatar, Ismail Haniyeh, said Thursday that the "fore" group will send a delegation to Egypt with the aim of an agreement that " meets the demands of our people". Haniyeh also said that Hamas is studying the latest Israeli proposal with "a positive spirit". Any agreement reached would be the first after a one week break in November which saw the exchange of 80 Israeli hostages with 240 Palestinian prisoners.<br> &nbsp;

